        <Abstract>
          <AbstractText Label="Background" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">
            Time-lapse embryo imaging has been proposed as a non-invasive method to improve embryo selection in IVF cycles. However, evidence from large randomized trials remains limited.
          </AbstractText>
          <AbstractText Label="Methods" NlmCategory="METHODS">
            We conducted a multicenter randomized controlled trial involving 1,200 patients undergoing IVF treatment. Patients were randomly assigned to embryo selection using time-lapse imaging (n=600) or standard morphological assessment (n=600). The primary outcome was live birth rate per embryo transfer.
          </AbstractText>
          <AbstractText Label="Results" NlmCategory="RESULTS">
            The live birth rate was significantly higher in the time-lapse group compared to the control group (48.2% vs. 39.5%, relative risk 1.22, 95% CI 1.06-1.40, p=0.006). Clinical pregnancy rate and implantation rate were also significantly improved.
          </AbstractText>
          <AbstractText Label="Conclusions" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">
            Time-lapse embryo imaging significantly improves live birth rates compared to standard morphological assessment in IVF patients. This technology should be considered for routine clinical practice.
          </AbstractText>
        </Abstract>
